# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vite-build
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] When you run `vite` for the first time, Vite prebundles your project dependencies before loading your site locally.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] It is done automatically and transparently by default.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] This is Vite performing what we call "dependency pre-bundling".
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] **Performance:** Vite converts ESM dependencies with many internal modules into a single module to improve subsequent page load performance.Some packages ship their ES modules builds as many separate files importing one another.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] For example, `lodash-es` has over 600 internal modules!
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] When we do `import { debounce } from 'lodash-es'`, the browser fires off 600+ HTTP requests at the same time!
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Even though the server has no problem handling them, the large number of requests creates network congestion on the browser side, causing the page to load noticeably slower.By pre-bundling `lodash-es` into a single module, we now only need one HTTP request instead!
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Dependency pre-bundling only applies in development mode.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] If an existing cache is not found, Vite will crawl your source code and automatically discover dependency imports (i.e.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] "bare imports" that expect to be resolved from `node_modules`) and use these found imports as entry points for the pre-bundle.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] The pre-bundling is performed with Rolldown, so it's typically very fast.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] After the server has already started, if a new dependency import is encountered that isn't already in the cache, Vite will re-run the dep bundling process and reload the page if needed.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] In a monorepo setup, a dependency may be a linked package from the same repo.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Vite automatically detects dependencies that are not resolved from `node_modules` and treats the linked dep as source code.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] It will not attempt to bundle the linked dep, and will analyze the linked dep's dependency list instead.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] However, this requires the linked dep to be exported as ESM.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] If not, you can add the dependency to `optimizeDeps.include` in your config.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] When making changes to the linked dep, restart the dev server with the `--force` command line option for the changes to take effect.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] The default dependency discovery heuristics may not always be desirable.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] In cases where you want to explicitly include/exclude dependencies from the list, use the `optimizeDeps` config options.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] A typical use case for `optimizeDeps.include` or `optimizeDeps.exclude` is when you have an import that is not directly discoverable in the source code.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] For example, maybe the import is created as a result of a plugin transform.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] This means Vite won't be able to discover the import on the initial scan - it can only discover it after the file is requested by the browser and transformed.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] This will cause the server to immediately re-bundle after server start.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Both `include` and `exclude` can be used to deal with this.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] If the dependency is large (with many internal modules) or is CommonJS, then you should include it; If the dependency is small and is already valid ESM, you can exclude it and let the browser load it directly.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] You can further customize Rolldown too with the `optimizeDeps.rolldownOptions` option.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] For example, adding a Rolldown plugin to handle special files in dependencies or changing the build `target`.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Vite caches the pre-bundled dependencies in `node_modules/.vite`.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] The pre-bundling step will only need to be re-run when one of the above has changed.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] If for some reason you want to force Vite to re-bundle deps, you can either start the dev server with the `--force` command line option, or manually delete the `node_modules/.vite` cache directory.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Resolved dependency requests are strongly cached with HTTP headers `max-age=31536000,immutable` to improve page reload performance during dev.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Once cached, these requests will never hit the dev server again.
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] They are auto invalidated by the appended version query if a different version is installed (as reflected in your package manager lockfile).
[src:vite-build/dep-pre-bundling] Restart Vite dev server with the `--force` flag to re-bundle the deps.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] At the very basic level, developing using Vite is not that different from using a static file server.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] However, Vite provides many enhancements over native ESM imports to support various features that are typically seen in bundler-based setups.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The above import will throw an error in the browser.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Rewrite the imports to valid URLs like `/node_modules/.vite/deps/my-dep.js?v=f3sf2ebd` so that the browser can import them properly.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite caches dependency requests via HTTP headers, so if you wish to locally edit/debug a dependency, follow the steps here.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite provides an HMR API over native ESM.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Frameworks with HMR capabilities can leverage the API to provide instant, precise updates without reloading the page or blowing away application state.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite provides first-party HMR integrations for Vue Single File Components and React Fast Refresh.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] There are also official integrations for Preact via @prefresh/vite.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Note you don't need to manually set these up - when you create an app via `create-vite`, the selected templates would have these pre-configured for you already.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite supports importing `.ts` files out of the box.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Note that Vite only performs transpilation on `.ts` files and does **NOT** perform type checking.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] It assumes type checking is taken care of by your IDE and build process.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The reason Vite does not perform type checking as part of the transform process is because the two jobs work fundamentally differently.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Transpilation can work on a per-file basis and aligns perfectly with Vite's on-demand compile model.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In comparison, type checking requires knowledge of the entire module graph.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Shoe-horning type checking into Vite's transform pipeline will inevitably compromise Vite's speed benefits.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite's job is to get your source modules into a form that can run in the browser as fast as possible.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To that end, we recommend separating static analysis checks from Vite's transform pipeline.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] This principle applies to other static analysis checks such as ESLint.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite uses Oxc Transformer to transpile TypeScript into JavaScript which is faster than vanilla `tsc`, and HMR updates can reflect in the browser in under 50ms.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite respects some of the options in `tsconfig.json` and sets the corresponding Oxc Transformer options.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] For each file, Vite uses the closest parent `tsconfig.json` that matches the file, or a config referenced by its `references` field that matches the file.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite treats a config as matching the file when the file satisfies the config's `files`, `include`, and `exclude` fields.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] When the options are set in both the Vite config and the `tsconfig.json`, the value in the Vite config takes precedence.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Some configuration fields under `compilerOptions` in `tsconfig.json` require special attention.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] It is because Oxc transformer only performs transpilation without type information, it doesn't support certain features like const enum and implicit type-only imports.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] You must set `"isolatedModules": true` in your `tsconfig.json` under `compilerOptions`, so that TS will warn you against the features that do not work with isolated transpilation.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If a dependency doesn't work well with `"isolatedModules": true`, you can use `"skipLibCheck": true` to temporarily suppress the errors until it is fixed upstream.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The default value will be `true` if the TypeScript target is `ES2022` or newer including `ESNext`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] It is consistent with the behavior of TypeScript 4.3.2+.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Other TypeScript targets will default to `false`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] `true` is the standard ECMAScript runtime behavior.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If you are using a library that heavily relies on class fields, please be careful about the library's intended usage of it.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] While most libraries expect `"useDefineForClassFields": true`, you can explicitly set `useDefineForClassFields` to `false` if your library doesn't support it.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite ignores the `target` value in the `tsconfig.json`, following the same behavior as esbuild.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To specify the target in dev, the `oxc.target` option can be used, which defaults to `esnext` for minimal transpilation.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In builds, the `build.target` option takes higher priority over `oxc.target` and can also be set if needed.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] This option is only partially supported.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Full support requires type inference by the TypeScript compiler, which is not supported.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] See Oxc Transformer's documentation for details.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] `resolve.tsconfigPaths: true` can be specified to tell Vite to use the `paths` option in `tsconfig.json` to resolve imports.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Note that this feature has a performance cost and is discouraged by the TypeScript team to use this option to change the behavior of the external tools.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite starter templates have `"skipLibCheck": true` by default to avoid typechecking dependencies, as they may choose to only support specific versions and configurations of TypeScript.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] You can learn more at vuejs/vue-cli#5688.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite's default types are for its Node.js API.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Note that if `compilerOptions.types` is specified, only these packages will be included in the global scope (instead of all visible ”@types” packages).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To override the default typing, add a type definition file that contains your typings.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Then, add the type reference before `vite/client`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] HTML files stand front-and-center of a Vite project, serving as the entry points for your application, making it simple to build single-page and multi-page applications.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Assets referenced by HTML elements such as `<script type="module" src>` and `<link href>` are processed and bundled as part of the app.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To opt-out of HTML processing on certain elements, you can add the `vite-ignore` attribute on the element, which can be useful when referencing external assets or CDN.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] All modern frameworks maintain integrations with Vite.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Check out the Plugins Guide for more information.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] `.jsx` and `.tsx` files are also supported out of the box.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] JSX transpilation is also handled via Oxc Transformer.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Your framework of choice will already configure JSX out of the box (for example, Vue users should use the official @vitejs/plugin-vue-jsx plugin, which provides Vue 3 specific features including HMR, global component resolving, directives and slots).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If using JSX with your own framework, custom `jsxFactory` and `jsxFragment` can be configured using the `oxc` option.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Importing `.css` files will inject its content to the page via a `<style>` tag with HMR support.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite is pre-configured to support CSS `@import` inlining via `postcss-import`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite aliases are also respected for CSS `@import`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In addition, all CSS `url()` references, even if the imported files are in different directories, are always automatically rebased to ensure correctness.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] `@import` aliases and URL rebasing are also supported for Sass and Less files (see CSS Pre-processors).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If the project contains valid PostCSS config (any format supported by postcss-load-config, e.g.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] `postcss.config.js`), it will be automatically applied to all imported CSS.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Note that CSS minification will run after PostCSS and will use `build.cssTarget` option.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Any CSS file ending with `.module.css` is considered a CSS modules file.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] CSS modules behavior can be configured via the `css.modules` option.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If `css.modules.localsConvention` is set to enable camelCase locals (e.g.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Because Vite targets modern browsers only, it is recommended to use native CSS variables with PostCSS plugins that implement CSSWG drafts (e.g. postcss-nesting) and author plain, future-standards-compliant CSS.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] That said, Vite does provide built-in support for `.scss`, `.sass`, `.less`, `.styl` and `.stylus` files.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If using Vue single file components, this also automatically enables `<style lang="sass">` et al.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite improves `@import` resolving for Sass and Less so that Vite aliases are also respected.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In addition, relative `url()` references inside imported Sass/Less files that are in different directories from the root file are also automatically rebased to ensure correctness.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Rebasing `url()` references that start with a variable or a interpolation are not supported due to its API constraints.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] `@import` alias and url rebasing are not supported for Stylus due to its API constraints.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] You can also use CSS modules combined with pre-processors by prepending `.module` to the file extension, for example `style.module.scss`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The automatic injection of CSS contents can be turned off via the `?inline` query parameter.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In this case, the processed CSS string is returned as the module's default export as usual, but the styles aren't injected to the page.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Default and named imports from CSS files (e.g `import style from './foo.css'`) are removed since Vite 5.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite uses Lightning CSS to minify CSS in production builds by default.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] However, PostCSS is still used for other CSS processing.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] There is experimental support for using Lightning CSS for CSS processing entirely.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] You can opt into it by adding `css.transformer: 'lightningcss'`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To configure it, you can pass Lightning CSS options to the `css.lightningcss` config option.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To configure CSS Modules, you should use `css.lightningcss.cssModules` instead of `css.modules` (which configures the way PostCSS handles CSS modules).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Matched files are by default lazy-loaded via dynamic import and will be split into separate chunks during build.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Negative glob patterns are also supported (prefixed with `!`).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] It's possible to only import parts of the modules with the `import` options.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] When combined with `eager` it's even possible to have tree-shaking enabled for those modules.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Set `import` to `default` to import the default export.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The base option can only be a directory path relative to the importer file or absolute against the project root.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Aliases and virtual modules aren't supported.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Only the globs that are relative paths are interpreted as relative to the resolved base.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] All the resulting module keys are modified to be relative to the base if provided.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] By default, glob pattern matching is case-sensitive.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] With `caseSensitive: false`, the glob will match files regardless of case (e.g., `Module.js`, `module.js`, `MODULE.js` will all be matched by `module*.js`).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Similar to glob import, Vite also supports dynamic import with variables.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Note that variables only represent file names one level deep.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If `file` is `'foo/bar'`, the import would fail.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] For more advanced usage, you can use the glob import feature.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] These rules are enforced to prevent accidentally importing files that are not intended to be bundled.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] For example, without these rules, `import(foo)` would bundle everything in the file system.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite supports importing pre-compiled `.wasm` files in two ways: directly as an ES module when you only need the module's exports, or with `?init` when you need explicit control over instantiation.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] A `.wasm` file can be imported directly.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If the WebAssembly module declares imports of its own, Vite resolves them from JavaScript modules.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Each import's module name is treated as an import specifier (resolved relative to the `.wasm` file) and the requested members are wired into the instance automatically.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] This follows the WebAssembly/ES Module Integration proposal.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Because a WebAssembly module is instantiated asynchronously, a directly imported `.wasm` file behaves as an async module and requires top-level `await` support.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Since the types of `.wasm` files are unknown, TypeScript will report errors like `Module '"*.wasm"' has no exported member 'add'`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To fix this, enable `allowArbitraryExtensions` in your `tsconfig.json` and create a declaration file next to your `.wasm` file.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] With `allowArbitraryExtensions` enabled, TypeScript will look for a declaration file named `{filename}.d.wasm.ts` when resolving a `.wasm` import.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] When you need control over when and how the module is instantiated, import it with `?init`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In the production build, `.wasm` files smaller than `assetInlineLimit` will be inlined as base64 strings.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Otherwise, they will be treated as a static asset and fetched on-demand.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Due to the lack of a universal way to load a file, the internal implementation for both direct `.wasm` imports and `.wasm?init` relies on the `node:fs` module.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] This means that these features will only work in Node.js compatible runtimes for SSR builds.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] A web worker script can be imported using `new Worker()` and `new SharedWorker()`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Compared to the worker suffixes, this syntax leans closer to the standards and is the **recommended** way to create workers.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The worker detection will only work if the `new URL()` constructor is used directly inside the `new Worker()` declaration.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Otherwise it is handled as a static asset URL instead.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Additionally, all options parameters must be static values (i.e. string literals).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] A web worker script can be directly imported by appending `?worker` or `?sharedworker` to the import request.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The worker script can also use ESM `import` statements instead of `importScripts()`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] **Note**: During development this relies on browser native support, but for the production build it is compiled away.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] By default, the worker script will be emitted as a separate chunk in the production build.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] See Worker Options for details on configuring the bundling of all workers.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To deploy CSP, certain directives or configs must be set due to Vite's internals.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] When `html.cspNonce` is set, Vite adds a nonce attribute with the specified value to any `<script>` and `<style>` tags, as well as `<link>` tags for stylesheets and module preloading.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Additionally, when this option is set, Vite will inject a meta tag (`<meta property="csp-nonce" nonce="PLACEHOLDER" />`).
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The nonce value of a meta tag with `property="csp-nonce"` will be used by Vite whenever necessary during both dev and after build.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Ensure that you replace the placeholder with a unique value for each request.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] This is important to prevent bypassing a resource's policy, which can otherwise be easily done.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] By default, during build, Vite inlines small assets as data URIs.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Allowing `data:` for related directives (e.g.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] `img-src`, `font-src`), or, disabling it by setting `build.assetsInlineLimit: 0` is necessary.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] It will allow injection of arbitrary scripts.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite can generate a file of all the dependencies' licenses used in the build with the `build.license` option.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] It can be hosted to display and acknowledge the dependencies used by the app.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To serve the file at a different path, you can pass `{ fileName: 'license.md' }` for example, so that it's served at `https://example.com/license.md`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] See the `build.license` docs for more information.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite automatically extracts the CSS used by modules in an async chunk and generates a separate file for it.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] The CSS file is automatically loaded via a `<link>` tag when the associated async chunk is loaded, and the async chunk is guaranteed to only be evaluated after the CSS is loaded to avoid FOUC.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If you'd rather have all the CSS extracted into a single file, you can disable CSS code splitting by setting `build.cssCodeSplit` to `false`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite automatically generates `<link rel="modulepreload">` directives for entry chunks and their direct imports in the built HTML.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In real world applications, Rollup often generates "common" chunks - code that is shared between two or more other chunks.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] In the non-optimized scenarios, when async chunk `A` is imported, the browser will have to request and parse `A` before it can figure out that it also needs the common chunk `C`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] It is possible for `C` to have further imports, which will result in even more roundtrips in the un-optimized scenario.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Vite's optimization will trace all the direct imports to completely eliminate the roundtrips regardless of import depth.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To improve the cache hit rate of chunks, Vite can create an import map for chunks.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] This prevents the cascading cache invalidation issue, which is a problem with ES Modules.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If `C` is updated, the only chunk that inherently needs to be invalidated is `C`.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] However, if `A` references `C` via a normal URL in a static import (i.e. the hash of `C` is included in the URL), the content of `A` is changed, thus `A` would also need to be invalidated.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] By utilizing the import maps feature, this issue can be avoided.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] When this optimization is enabled, Vite will create an import map that maps each chunk's ID to its URL and uses the chunk ID in the import statements instead of the URL.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] This way, when a chunk is updated, only the updated chunk needs to be invalidated, while the chunks that reference it will not be invalidated.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] Note that this optimization currently does not apply to CSS and assets.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] If you update an asset, the chunks that reference it will be invalidated.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] That said, the invalidation would not cascade and the chunk importing the invalidated chunk would not be invalidated.
[src:vite-build/guide-features] To enable this feature, set `build.chunkImportMap` to `true`.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] As web applications have grown in size and complexity, the tools used to build them have struggled to keep up.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Developers working on large projects have experienced painfully slow dev server startups, sluggish hot updates, and long production build times.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Each generation of build tooling has improved on the last, but these problems have persisted.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Rather than incrementally improving existing approaches, it rethought how code should be served during development.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Since then, Vite has evolved through multiple major versions, each time adapting to new capabilities in the ecosystem: from leveraging native ES modules in the browser, to adopting a fully Rust-powered toolchain.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Today, Vite powers many frameworks and tools.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Its architecture is designed to evolve with the web platform rather than lock into any single approach, making it a foundation you can build on for the long term.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] When Vite was first created, browsers had just gained wide support for ES modules (ESM), a way to load JavaScript files directly, without needing a tool to bundle them into a single file first.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Traditional build tools (often called *bundlers*) would process your entire application upfront before anything could be shown in the browser.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] The larger the app, the longer you waited.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] This meant dev server startup was nearly instant, regardless of application size.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] When you edited a file, Vite used Hot Module Replacement (HMR) over native ESM to update just that module in the browser, without a full page reload or waiting for a rebuild.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Vite was not the first tool to explore this approach.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Snowpack pioneered unbundled development and inspired Vite's dependency pre-bundling.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] WMR by the Preact team inspired the universal plugin API that works in both dev and build. @web/dev-server influenced Vite 1.0's server architecture.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Vite built on these ideas and carried them forward.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Even though unbundled ESM works well during development, shipping it in production is still inefficient due to additional network round trips from nested imports.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] That's why bundling is still necessary for optimized production builds.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] As Vite matured, frameworks began adopting it as their build layer.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Its plugin API, based on Rollup's conventions, made integration natural without requiring frameworks to work around Vite's internals.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Nuxt, SvelteKit, Astro, React Router, Analog, SolidStart, and others chose Vite as their foundation.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Tools like Vitest and Storybook built on it too, extending Vite's reach beyond app bundling.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Backend frameworks like Laravel and Ruby on Rails integrated Vite for their frontend asset pipelines.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] The ecosystem shaped Vite as much as Vite shaped the ecosystem.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] The Vite team runs vite-ecosystem-ci, which tests major ecosystem projects against every Vite change.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Ecosystem health is not an afterthought.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Vite originally relied on two separate tools under the hood: esbuild for fast compilation during development, and Rollup for thorough optimization in production builds.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] This worked, but maintaining two pipelines introduced inconsistencies: different transformation behaviors, separate plugin systems, and growing glue code to keep them aligned.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Rolldown was built to unify both into a single bundler: written in Rust for native speed, and compatible with the same plugin API the ecosystem already relied on.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] It uses Oxc for parsing, transforming, and minifying.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] This gives Vite an end-to-end toolchain where the build tool, bundler, and compiler are maintained together and evolve as a unit.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] The result is one consistent pipeline from development to production.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] The migration was done carefully: a technical preview shipped first so early adopters could validate the change, ecosystem CI caught compatibility issues early, and a compatibility layer preserved existing configurations.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Vite's architecture continues to evolve.
[src:vite-build/guide-why] Vite's goal is not to be the final tool, but to be one that keeps evolving with the web platform, and with the developers building on it.
[src:vite-build/module-bundler] A **module bundler** is a software development tool that takes multiple source files and their dependencies (*modules*) and combines them into one or more output files called *bundles*.
[src:vite-build/module-bundler] Module bundlers are commonly used in front-end web development to package JavaScript, CSS and other assets for efficient delivery to web browsers.
[src:vite-build/module-bundler] Module bundlers typically start from one or more entry points and build a dependency graph of all imported modules before producing the final bundles, often applying optimisations such as minification and tree shaking.
[src:vite-build/tree-shaking] It relies on the import and export statements to detect if code modules are exported and imported for use between JavaScript files.
[src:vite-build/tree-shaking] In modern JavaScript applications, we use module bundlers (e.g., webpack or Rollup) to automatically remove dead code when bundling multiple JavaScript files into single files.
[src:vite-build/tree-shaking] This is important for preparing code that is production ready, for example with clean structures and minimal file size.
[src:vite-build/vite] Vite monitors files as they are being edited and upon file save the web browser reloads the code being edited through a process called Hot Module Replacement (HMR) which works by just reloading the specific file being changed using ES6 modules (ESM) instead of recompiling the entire application.
[src:vite-build/vite] Vite provides built-in support for server-side rendering (SSR).
[src:vite-build/vite] By default, it listens on TCP port 5173.
[src:vite-build/vite] It is possible to configure Vite to serve content over HTTPS and proxy requests (including WebSocket) to a back-end web server, such as Apache HTTP Server or lighttpd.
[src:vite-build/vite] Vite has a Hot Module Replacement (HMR) system, which reduces wait times during development.
[src:vite-build/vite] Vite supports frameworks such as React, Vue, and Svelte, and has server-side rendering (SSR), code-splitting, and asynchronous loading.
